post_text:
BSSD Staff, Students, and Families

BSSD has just learned of the recent arrest of Donteh Devoe in Anchorage on Sexual Abuse of a Minor charges. Although everyone is presumed innocent until proven guilty, I have terminated all future contracts with Mr. Devoe and any of his associated organizations immediately. In addition, BSSD will not enter into any further contracts.

If anyone has been personally affected by Mr. Devoe while he has worked with BSSD, please contact myself or Kris Busk in the District Office as soon as possible. Proper authorities can also be contacted at the link provided below.

Safety of our entire BSSD family is our most important duty. We will continue to ensure a safe educational experience for all.

Our thoughts and prayers are with the affected families across the state.

Respectfully,

Dr. Bobby Bolen

https://local.nixle.com/alert/7814562/

post_text: Congratulations Ben Pungowiyi for all your work and talents in Savoonga.
shared_text:
Senator Dan Sullivan
December 6, 2019 at 1:40 PM ·

This week, I met with master Alaska Native Ivory carver Ben Pungowiyi from Savoonga, a community known as the “walrus capital of the world” with a rich history of ivory and bone carvings that has been passed down for thousands of years. Ben began ivory carving at the age of six, and hunting around the same time. Ben was recently in DC to present at the Department of Interior with Indian Arts and Crafts Board specialists Lars Krutak, Ph.D, and Ken Van Wey. Savoonga’s economy is almost entirely dependent on the ability to sell ivory that has come from walrus and fossilized walrus ivory. In the Senate, I have introduced the 𝙀𝙢𝙥𝙤𝙬𝙚𝙧𝙞𝙣𝙜 𝙍𝙪𝙧𝙖𝙡 𝙀𝙘𝙤𝙣𝙤𝙢𝙞𝙚𝙨 𝙏𝙝𝙧𝙤𝙪𝙜𝙝 𝘼𝙡𝙖𝙨𝙠𝙖 𝙉𝙖𝙩𝙞𝙫𝙚 𝙎𝙪𝙨𝙩𝙖𝙞𝙣𝙖𝙗𝙡𝙚 𝘼𝙧𝙩𝙨 𝙖𝙣𝙙 𝙃𝙖𝙣𝙙𝙞𝙘𝙧𝙖𝙛𝙩𝙨 𝘼𝙘𝙩 to protect Alaska Native artists, like Ben, from state bans on walrus ivory, whale bone, and other marine mammal products that have been legally carved under federal law. It is so important that we support our Alaska Native artists and craftsmen.
text:
Congratulations Ben Pungowiyi for all your work and talents in Savoonga.

Senator Dan Sullivan
December 6, 2019 at 1:40 PM ·

This week, I met with master Alaska Native Ivory carver Ben Pungowiyi from Savoonga, a community known as the “walrus capital of the world” with a rich history of ivory and bone carvings that has been passed down for thousands of years. Ben began ivory carving at the age of six, and hunting around the same time. Ben was recently in DC to present at the Department of Interior with Indian Arts and Crafts Board specialists Lars Krutak, Ph.D, and Ken Van Wey. Savoonga’s economy is almost entirely dependent on the ability to sell ivory that has come from walrus and fossilized walrus ivory. In the Senate, I have introduced the 𝙀𝙢𝙥𝙤𝙬𝙚𝙧𝙞𝙣𝙜 𝙍𝙪𝙧𝙖𝙡 𝙀𝙘𝙤𝙣𝙤𝙢𝙞𝙚𝙨 𝙏𝙝𝙧𝙤𝙪𝙜𝙝 𝘼𝙡𝙖𝙨𝙠𝙖 𝙉𝙖𝙩𝙞𝙫𝙚 𝙎𝙪𝙨𝙩𝙖𝙞𝙣𝙖𝙗𝙡𝙚 𝘼𝙧𝙩𝙨 𝙖𝙣𝙙 𝙃𝙖𝙣𝙙𝙞𝙘𝙧𝙖𝙛𝙩𝙨 𝘼𝙘𝙩 to protect Alaska Native artists, like Ben, from state bans on walrus ivory, whale bone, and other marine mammal products that have been legally carved under federal law. It is so important that we support our Alaska Native artists and craftsmen.

2019 Creative Native Call for Art Announcement

Center for Native American Youth
July 30, 2019 at 6:17 AM ·

CALLING ALL CREATIVE NATIVES AGES 5-24:

Creative Native is a call for art that supports young Indigenous artists ages 5-24 years old by providing them an opportunity to receive national recognition, funding for art supplies, and award of $200.

This year's Call for Art prompt centers around the Census and Citizenship, asking youth to answer the prompt: I am a Native youth and I count. What does citizenship and sense of belonging mean to me?

Art is due by August 9, 2019 11:59 PM EST. Each age group will have a winner that will receive $200, a $50 gift card for art supplies, a Gen-I certificate, T-shirt, and their art will be featured throughout the State of Native Youth Report and on our website; with one grand prize winner in the 15-24 age category being featured on the cover of the State of Native Youth Report and joining us in DC for the release event and panel.

Find more information about Creative Native and how to submit your art here:

Bering Strait School District: Special Education Department
April 24, 2019 at 10:46 PM ·

The kids were able to learn more about job opportunities today. First stop was a fish hatchery where we explored jobs in the fisheries industry. Next stop, was the radio station. A few kids got to be recorded. Then, we went to Barnacle Foods to learn all about their local food product——kelp salsa and kelp pickles. Delicious! We learned about jobs in small business and entrepreneurship. The kids worked on their future job slide shows. We ended our evening with a Mexican Style dinner, followed by a lovely hike to Mendenhall Glacier and Nugget Falls. Juneau is beautiful and we have #thebestkidsever!

You can find more information about the contest here: https://www.fws.gov/birds/education/junior-duck-stamp-conservation-program/junior-duck-stamp-contest-information.php

post_text:
Trailblazers Wanted - Apply by April 9th

The Student Conservation Association (SCA) is recruiting students age 15-19 for summer trail/environmental restoration projects. Students from all over Alaska convene to camp out, build trails, cookout, and share work skills and life skills. Teams of eight crew members are supervised by two adult crew leaders. In addition to community service hours, school credit, and skill-sharing, students get a $250 or $500 stipend at the successful completion of their two or four weeks of service. Outdoor gear, food, and transportation (if needed) are all provided. Students must be available for at least one of the crews in order to be considered.

To apply, students must visit https://www.thesca.org/serve/program/alaska-regional-crews and complete the Basic, Program (Regional/National Crew), and Final application.

Candidates do not need to pay the $25 application fee. Enter application code PO-00726601 for a fee waiver.

We are so excited to meet all the 2019 Alaska State Poetry Out Loud Finalists in Juneau! Congratulations to Kiana Vesel representing Academy Charter School in Palmer; Florence Sarren representing Frank A. Degnan High School in Unalakleet; Honor Mealey representing North Pole High School; Natalie Fraser representing West Anchorage High School; Morgan Blackgoat representing Thunder Mountain High School in Juneau; Talisa McKinley representing Ketchikan High School; Iris Downey representing Homer High School; Moriah Jacobsen representing Glennallen High School; Avery Herrman-Sakamoto representing Petersburg High School; Eliana Zimmerman representing Tanalian School in Port Alsworth! We look forward to hearing your voices in the Alaska State Finals of the Poetry Out Loud: National Recitation Contest, tomorrow at 5pm at the 360 North Studio in Juneau! For those who can't join us in Juneau, please tune in to the live webcast on Thursday, March 7th at 5 pm at https://www.360north.org/.

The Nome Arts Council and Katirvik Cultural Center are planning the fifth annual Alappaa Film Festival for Tuesday & Wednesday, March 5-6!

They are seeking original films that are:
- 10 minutes or less (even one minute) in length
- Related to life in the far north (take it where you will!)
- Not just home video footage, but edited/produced short films
- In digital format (.mov files on DVD, flash drive, or by email; no VHS, please)

DEADLINE TO SUBMIT: WEDNESDAY, FEB. 20.

https://www.facebook.com/events/2120109711368175/
